==English==
===Etymology===
either directly or through French ''floride,'' < Latin ''floridus,'' from ''flor-, flos'' flower
===Adjective===
#'''a.'''  ''obsolete:'' blooming with flowers; abounding in or covered with flowers; flowery. '''b.''' consisting of flowers, floral. 
#''figrative:'' profusely adorned as with flowers; elaborately or luxuriantly ornate. often in somewhat disparaging sense: excessively ornate. '''a.''' of composition, speech, etc.: abounding in ornaments or flowers of rhetoric; full of fine words and phrases; flowery '''b.''' of a person or his attributes: addicted to the use of flowery language or rhetorical ornament. '''c.''' of attire, manners, methods of procedure, etc.: highly ornate; showy, [[ostentatious]]
# '''a.''' ''architecture:'' enriched with decorative details. '''b.''' of music or [[counterpoint]]: ornate and embellished: full of elaboration: [[figurate|FIGURATE]]
#''obsolete:'' of blooming appearance; strikingly beautiful or attractive; brilliant. of color: bright, [[resplendent]]
#'''a.''' of the complexion (or the colour of a part of the body): rosy or [[ruddy]], flushed with red. '''b.''' of the blood: bright red (i.e. arterial)
#''now rare:'' flourishing, lively, vigorous; in the bloom of health